          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       ​​eBay’s learning moment
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Meg Whitman, eBay’s then-CEO, wanted to transform the online platform into a full-fledged e-commerce ecosystem. She believed that integrating Skype would do just that. Their logic was that the marketplace would be even better if customers and sellers could cut out the middleman and the confusion around product details, if they could just get in touch directly.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/ebay-ip-lawsuit-google-microsoft-exit.jpg" alt="The European entrepreneurs sued eBay for misusing their IP, leading Google and Microsoft to think twice about buying the company from eBay" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
           The European entrepreneurs sued eBay for misusing their IP, leading Google and Microsoft to think twice about buying the company from eBay. Credits: Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         But Skype’s founders warned eBay that the platform wasn’t designed for integration into an e-commerce marketplace. However, eBay proceeded to acquire the company and invested $2.6B in 2005. By 2007, it became clear that it was one of the poor acquisition ideas, as the asynchronous nature of both businesses meant there was no cultural fit, no operational overlap, and no genuine user demand. 
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           In 2009, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-19-07-2025-ebay-sold-skype" target="_blank">eBay sold 65% of Skype</a> to a group of investors for just $1.9B. It retained a 35% stake, later selling it to Microsoft when the company acquired Skype for $8.5B in 2011. The takeaway may seem rather obvious: listen to your users and escape buying into trends.
            </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
