        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       Microsoft and Nokia couldn't connect
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     Microsoft had a grand vision to turn itself into a “devices and services” company. In 2011, Microsoft and Nokia formed a strategic alliance, where Nokia would ditch Symbian and adopt Windows Mobile as its exclusive OS. Thus, the Lumia line was born, which was praised for its bold design, powerful camera, and a user interface that was not-so-appealing to some but ahead of its time for others. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/microsoft-consent-decision-business-merger.jpg" alt="Microsoft applied for a consent decision, which includes preventive measures against unfair business practices resulting from the business combination" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
          Microsoft applied for a consent decision, which includes preventive measures against unfair business practices resulting from the business combination. Credits: Business Korea</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           By 2013, Nokia’s mobile business was bleeding currency, and Microsoft's then-CEO, Steve Ballmer, pitched a bold plan to acquire Nokia’s mobile division for $7.2B. The board was hesitant, but they proceeded with the acquisition. Unfortunately, they completely misread the market. Since fewer Windows mobiles were sold, there was less incentive for developers to make apps for the platform, leaving their App Store unsupported and underwhelmed. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      In 2015, Satya Nadella reversed course. He wrote $7.6B from the agreement, more than the original market value. Around 25,000 Nokia employees experienced layoffs. In 2016, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-19-07-2025-microsoft-sold-nokia-feature-mobile-business" target="_blank">Microsoft sold Nokia’s mobile business</a>, which faced a humiliating exit to HMD Global and Foxconn for just $ 350M. Nokia’s smartphone division had been reduced to a licensing brand. In technology, early movers will always have an advantage.  
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
