    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="4px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
     Quaker's costly snap decision 
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     By 1994, Snapple had built a cult following among health-conscious and tech-savvy urbanites through its quirky advertising, unusual flavors, and handwritten labels. Quaker Oats, which saw triumph with Gatorade, sought to replicate the same with Snapple. CEO William Smithburg pitched Snapple to his board as a "category complement" to Gatorade. He made a $1.7B all-cash bid, outbidding Coca-Cola and other suitors by a significant margin.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/quaker-oats-snapple-merger-dynamics.jpg" alt="Quaker Oats had the distribution channels and the marketing muscle, while Snapple had the innovative products and a loyal customer base" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
          Quaker Oats had the distribution channels and the advertising muscle, while Snapple had the innovative products and a loyal customer base. Credits: Time for design</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Snapple thrived on small-scale distribution, especially in delis, mom-and-pop stores, gas stations, and campus vending machines. When Quaker forced Snapple into big-box retail chains and supermarkets, firing independent distributors in the process, it instantly destroyed Snapple’s core markets and alienated longtime consumers. The unique Snapple personality was also washed down to fit Quaker’s corporate style. 
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     By 1996, just 27 months after the acquisition, Snapple’s business had flatlined. Quaker was losing a significant amount annually on the brand, and Smithburg was under scrutiny from shareholders. Quaker knew it was time to cut losses and <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-19-07-2025-sold-snapple-to-triarc-technologies" target="_blank">sold Snapple to Triarc Companies</a> for just $300M at a loss $1.4B in under two and a half years. Smithburg resigned in disgrace later that year.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
